DataObj / GrokThink framework
==============================

A C framework for a node-based dataflow object system. Loadable object
modules (.object files) are discovered on disk at startup, dlopen'd, and
register themselves into a live node tree. Everything - metadata, state,
wiring, even function pointers - is stored as properties on nodes. It's a
ground-up rewrite of VNOS (Singlestep Technologies, early 2000s).

Three rules the whole system is built on:
  - Everything is a node: one tree structure holds the registry,
    configuration, and wiring.
  - Everything is a message: objects only ever talk to each other through
    subscriptions between ports.
  - The app is an empty view: the executable is a hollow host, the loaded
    objects are the functionality. A different product is different
    objects and a different flow, never a different binary.

See CLAUDE.md for the full architecture writeup and ROADMAP.md for where
this is headed.


Build
-----

    make depend
    make

To clean up:

    make clean


Run
---

    export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=$LD_LIBRARY_PATH:.
    ./framework

or just

    ./framework.sh

For help:

    ./framework.sh --help

Options:

    -h              This help screen
    -d              Become a server process
    -ip <address>   Address to bind the web GUI to: 127.0.0.1 for
                    this machine only, 0.0.0.0 to be reachable from
                    the network (default 0.0.0.0)
    -l <logfile>    Logfile to output debug info
    -p              Print Main Nodes on exit
    -port <number>  Port to serve the web GUI on (default 8083)
    -t              Perform unit testing of library functions
    -v <number>     Verbose level from 0 to 9, inclusive


Web GUI
-------

`./framework` also brings up a browser-based visual canvas on
http://localhost:8083 by default - the bind address and port are set
with the -ip and -port options above, so e.g.

    ./framework -ip 0.0.0.0 -port 8083

serves the canvas to the whole LAN at http://<your-ip>:8083. Drag
object classes out of the palette, drop them
on the canvas, wire ports together by clicking, and watch/drive them
through live instrument widgets (sliders, LEDs, checkboxes, VU meters,
buttons). Every drag, wire, and value change is a real message through the
same object graph the C side runs on - there is no separate client-side
simulation of the flow.

The whole session (every instance, wire, and property value) can be saved
to and reloaded from a flow file (the File menu in the UI), so a canvas
you build survives a restart.

Everything on the canvas is live: chaining widgets together (e.g. a
slider driving a dozen others in sequence) propagates each change through
the scheduler's message queue immediately, so a rapid drag on the first
control snaps every downstream one in lock-step with no visible lag, even
over a plain browser WebSocket connection.

There's also a raw JSON control protocol on port 8091 (and an
authenticated variant on 8093) for driving the same object graph without
a browser - see the Bridge section of CLAUDE.md.
